Terraform is an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tool developed by HashiCorp that lets you define, provision, and manage cloud infrastructure using declarative configuration files. It’s widely used across AWS, Azure, GCP, and other providers for automating infrastructure deployment.

⚙️ Terraform End-to-End Workflow
Step	                    Description	                                             Example Command
1️⃣ Write Configuration---> Define resources in .tf files using HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language).---->	main.tf
2️⃣ Initialize--->Download provider plugins and set up the working directory.--->terraform init
3️⃣ Validate--->Check syntax and configuration correctness.--->terraform validate
4️⃣ Plan---> Preview changes Terraform will make to reach the desired state.-->terraform plan
5️⃣ Apply--->Execute the plan and create/update resources.-->terraform apply
6️⃣ Show--->Display the current state of infrastructure.-->terraform show
7️⃣ Destroy--->Remove all managed resources.-->terraform destroy


🧩 Key Concepts
Concept	                                         Meaning
Providers	                     Plugins that interact with cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, GCP, etc.).
Resources	                     Infrastructure components (EC2, S3, VPC, etc.).
Modules	                         Reusable groups of resources for modular design.
State File (terraform.tfstate)	 Tracks real-world infrastructure and configuration.
Variables & Outputs	             Parameterize configurations and expose results.
Backend	                         Defines where state is stored (local, S3, remote).

🏗️ Setup & Initialization
Command	                        Purpose	                                           Typical Use
terraform init|Initializes working directory and downloads provider plugins.|	First step after writing .tf files.
terraform fmt |Formats configuration files to standard style. |	Keeps code clean in CI/CD pipelines.
terraform validate |	Checks syntax and configuration correctness. |	Run before committing code.


📋 Planning & Execution
Command	|Purpose	|Typical Use
terraform plan	|Shows what changes will be made.|Used in pull requests or before apply.
terraform apply  |-auto-approve	|Executes plan and provisions resources.Used in automated pipelines.
terraform destroy |-auto-approve|Tears down infrastructure.	Used for cleanup in test environments.


🧩 State Management
Command	Purpose	Typical Use
terraform show	|Displays current state.	|Debugging or documentation.
terraform state list	|Lists all tracked resources.|	Verifying resource tracking.
terraform state rm <resource>	|Removes resource from state file.	|When manually deleting resources.
terraform refresh|	Updates state file with real cloud data.|	Sync after manual changes.


🌍 Workspaces & Environments
Command	Purpose	Typical Use
terraform workspace list	|Lists all workspaces.	|Managing dev/staging/prod.
terraform workspace new dev	|Creates a new workspace.|	Environment isolation.
terraform workspace select prod|	Switches workspace.	|Deploying to production.


🔐 Variables & Outputs
Command	Purpose	Typical Use
terraform output	|Displays output values.	|Fetching IPs, URLs, etc.
terraform output -json	|Outputs in JSON format.	|Integration with scripts.

